```typescript
function FileUploader() {
  const [file, setFile] = useState<File | null>(null);
  const [preview, setPreview] = useState<string | null>(null);
  const [progress, setProgress] = useState(0);

  const handleSelect = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    const selected = e.target.files?.[0];
    if (!selected) return;
    setFile(selected);
    setPreview(URL.createObjectURL(selected)); // creates a temporary local URL for the image
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    return () => { if (preview) URL.revokeObjectURL(preview); }; // cleanup: free the blob memory
  }, [preview]);

  const upload = () => {
    if (!file) return;
    const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
    xhr.upload.onprogress = (e) => setProgress(Math.round((e.loaded / e.total) * 100));
    xhr.onload = () => console.log('Upload complete');
    const formData = new FormData();
    formData.append('file', file);
    xhr.open('POST', '/api/upload');
    xhr.send(formData);
  };

  return (
    <>
      <input type="file" accept="image/*" onChange={handleSelect} />
      {preview && <img src={preview} alt="preview" width={100} />}
      {progress > 0 && <progress value={progress} max={100} />}
      <button onClick={upload} disabled={!file}>Upload</button>
    </>
  );
}
```

**Why XMLHttpRequest instead of fetch:** the plain `fetch` API's `Response` exposes a readable stream for *download* progress (reading the response body incrementally), but it has no built-in event for *upload* progress — there's no way to know how many bytes of the request body have actually been sent over the wire. `XMLHttpRequest.upload.onprogress` exposes exactly that. This is the practical reason libraries like axios still wrap XHR under the hood for upload progress bars, even in a fetch-first codebase — until a future Fetch API addition closes this gap, XHR remains necessary specifically for this one feature.

**Cleaning up the object URL:** `URL.createObjectURL` allocates a reference held by the browser pointing at the in-memory file blob; it isn't automatically garbage-collected when the component unmounts or the preview changes. Calling `URL.revokeObjectURL` in the effect's cleanup releases that reference — skipping it leaks memory for every file the user selects across the session, which compounds in a long-lived SPA where users select many files without a full page reload to clear it.

Common pitfall: calling `revokeObjectURL` immediately after setting the `src`/state instead of in cleanup tied to the *next* change or unmount — revoking too early breaks the preview because the browser drops the blob reference while the `<img>` is still trying to display it.

