### Lazy Loading and Code Splitting

Code splitting breaks the bundle into smaller chunks loaded on demand. `React.lazy` + `Suspense` provide native support: each `lazy()` call creates a separate chunk; bundlers (Webpack, Vite) detect `import()` calls and split automatically.

```typescript
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';
import { createBrowserRouter, RouterProvider, Outlet } from 'react-router-dom';
import { ErrorBoundary } from 'react-error-boundary';

// Each lazy() creates a separate bundle chunk — define at module level, not inside components
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'));
const Settings = lazy(
  () => import(/* webpackChunkName: "settings" */ './pages/Settings')
);

function PageWrapper() {
  return (
    // Always pair Suspense with an ErrorBoundary — chunk load can fail
    <ErrorBoundary fallbackRender={({ error }) => <div>Failed to load: {error.message}</div>}>
      <Suspense fallback={<div className="page-loader">Loading…</div>}>
        <Outlet />
      </Suspense>
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}

const router = createBrowserRouter([
  {
    path: '/',
    element: <PageWrapper />,
    children: [
      { path: 'dashboard', element: <Dashboard /> },
      { path: 'settings', element: <Settings /> },
    ],
  },
]);

export default function App() {
  return <RouterProvider router={router} />;
}

// Prefetch a chunk on hover to eliminate perceived load time
function NavLink({ to, chunkImport, children }: { to: string; chunkImport: () => Promise<unknown>; children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <a href={to} onMouseEnter={() => chunkImport()}>
      {children}
    </a>
  );
}
// <NavLink to="/settings" chunkImport={() => import('./pages/Settings')}>Settings</NavLink>
```

**Common interview trap:** Defining `lazy()` inside a component body — `const Comp = lazy(() => import('./X'))` inside a render creates a new Promise every render, bypassing React's cache and re-loading the chunk. Always define lazy components at the module (top) level. Second trap: forgetting an `ErrorBoundary` around lazy components — chunk download failures (network errors, new deploys mid-session) crash the UI without one.

answer.ru:
### Lazy Loading и Code Splitting

Code splitting разбивает бандл на меньшие чанки, загружаемые по требованию. `React.lazy` + `Suspense` обеспечивают нативную поддержку: каждый вызов `lazy()` создаёт отдельный чанк; бандлеры (Webpack, Vite) автоматически обнаруживают `import()`.

```typescript
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';
import { createBrowserRouter, RouterProvider, Outlet } from 'react-router-dom';
import { ErrorBoundary } from 'react-error-boundary';

// Каждый lazy() создаёт отдельный чанк — определяйте на уровне модуля, не внутри компонентов
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'));
const Settings = lazy(
  () => import(/* webpackChunkName: "settings" */ './pages/Settings')
);

function PageWrapper() {
  return (
    // Всегда сочетайте Suspense с ErrorBoundary — загрузка чанка может провалиться
    <ErrorBoundary fallbackRender={({ error }) => <div>Ошибка загрузки: {error.message}</div>}>
      <Suspense fallback={<div className="page-loader">Загрузка…</div>}>
        <Outlet />
      </Suspense>
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}

const router = createBrowserRouter([
  {
    path: '/',
    element: <PageWrapper />,
    children: [
      { path: 'dashboard', element: <Dashboard /> },
      { path: 'settings', element: <Settings /> },
    ],
  },
]);

export default function App() {
  return <RouterProvider router={router} />;
}

// Prefetch чанка при наведении — убирает задержку восприятия
function NavLink({ to, chunkImport, children }: { to: string; chunkImport: () => Promise<unknown>; children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <a href={to} onMouseEnter={() => chunkImport()}>
      {children}
    </a>
  );
}
```

**Типичная ошибка на интервью:** Определять `lazy()` внутри тела компонента — `const Comp = lazy(() => import('./X'))` внутри рендера создаёт новый Promise при каждом рендере, обходя кеш React и повторно загружая чанк. Всегда определяйте lazy-компоненты на уровне модуля (вверху файла). Вторая ловушка: забыть `ErrorBoundary` вокруг lazy-компонентов — ошибки загрузки чанка (сетевые ошибки, новый деплой в процессе сессии) без неё крашат весь UI.

answer.en:
### State Management Comparison

Context: built-in, good for simple global state (themes, auth), but causes unnecessary re-renders when unrelated state changes. Redux: centralized, predictable, DevTools, but boilerplate-heavy. Zustand: minimal, hook-based, no boilerplate, but smaller ecosystem.

Context for: theme, language, auth. Redux for: large apps with complex async flows, time-travel debugging needs. Zustand for: modern, small-to-medium apps wanting simplicity without Redux ceremony.

```typescript
// Zustand (recommended for modern apps)
import { create } from 'zustand';

const useStore = create((set) => ({
  user: null,
  setUser: (user) => set({ user }),
  logout: () => set({ user: null })
}));

// Use in components
function Profile() {
  const { user, logout } = useStore();
  return <button onClick={logout}>{user?.name}</button>;
}

// Context (simple use case)
const ThemeContext = createContext('light');
export function ThemeProvider({ children }) {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light');
  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}>
      {children}
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}```


**Common interview trap:** Candidates over-engineer with Redux for simple apps or use Context when they need selector memoization—understand trade-offs.

